&lt;p&gt;Canceling that one doesn&apos;t unstick anything, as the DC is not yet blocking waiting for a response to its commit/rollback.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&apos;ll need to give some thought as to how to get find-non-progressing-operation and cancel-non-progressing-operation to identify the 24068422 op as the problematic one, or at least to decide that they don&apos;t know which of the two is the problem, forcing the user to investigate further.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13029507" author="brian.stansberry" created="Tue, 23 Dec 2014 22:24:49 -0500"  >&lt;p&gt;The 1273140711 is identified as the problematic one because it is the op that holds the exclusive write lock on the HC process, and it has been holding it for a long time. The HC is simply acting as a proxy for the 24068422 op, so there is no need for it to acquire the exclusive write lock.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
